He juggles sorrow in the spotlight’s glare,
A marionette of mirth, stripped bare.
His shoes too big, his heart too small,
He stumbles, grinning through the fall.

Balloons rise—his hopes, helium-thin,
Each pop a memory caved within.
The crowd roars loud, a cruel refrain,
Their laughter echoing his pain.

Behind the greasepaint, tears congeal,
A circus act that’s all too real.
Yet still he bows, the curtain drawn—
A broken joke, performing on.
